{"questionId":"22263989","questionHtml":"<p>Show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ABCD</mi></math> is a parallelogram.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>AD</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>BC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>AB</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>DC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>One pair of opposite sides have equal length AND are parallel&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>AD</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mover><mi>BC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mover><mi>AB</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mover><mi>DC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong><em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>AD</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>BC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;</em></strong>and&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>AB</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>DC</mi><mo>→</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>both pairs of opposite sides are parallel (or have equal length)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>Both pairs of opposite angles are equal is also valid.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ABCD</mi></math>&nbsp;is a parallelogram&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22263989","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ2.8c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Show that ABCD is a parallelogram.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.10—Vector definitions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.13—Scalar and vector products"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}